│ An LLVM bug in the `constraint-elimination` pass is causing  │
│ a miscompilation. The issue stems from an incorrect analysis │
│ in Scalar Evolution (SCEV) for `mul nsw` instructions. When  │
│ analyzing a `mul nsw` with a constant operand, SCEV may      │
│ incorrectly produce a wrapped symbolic expression, failing   │
│ to account for the "no signed wrap" guarantee. This faulty   │
│ expression leads downstream passes like                      │
│ `constraint-elimination` to make invalid deductions.         │
│                                                              │
│ The fix involves enhancing `ScalarEvolution::getMulExpr` to  │
│ correctly handle the `nsw` flag. Specifically, when creating │
│ a SCEV expression for a `mul nsw` of the form `X * C` (where │
│ `C` is a constant), we must check if the multiplication      │
│ could overflow. If an overflow is possible, we cannot create │
│ a simple symbolic expression. Instead, we should return a    │
│ `SCEVUnknown`, which conservatively represents an            │
│ unanalyzable value. This prevents the optimizer from relying │
│ on a potentially incorrect symbolic representation and       │
│ avoids the miscompilation.                                   │
│                                                              │
│ The following patch applies this logic to                    │
│ `ScalarEvolution::getMulExpr`.                               │
│                                                              │
│ ```patch                                                     │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Analysis/ScalarEvolution.cpp                  │
│ +++ b/llvm/lib/Analysis/ScalarEvolution.cpp                  │
│ @@ -3138,15 +3138,11 @@                                      │
│        // If any of Add's ops are Adds or Muls with a        │
│ constant, apply this                                         │
│        // transformation as well.                            │
│        //                                                    │
│ -      // TODO: There are some cases where this              │
│ transformation is not                                        │
│ -      // profitable; for example, Add = (C0 + X) * Y + Z.   │
│ Maybe the scope of                                           │
│ -      // this transformation should be narrowed down.       │
│ -      if (Add->getNumOperands() == 2 &&                     │
│ containsConstantInAddMulChain(Add)) {                        │
│ +      // C1 * (C2+V) -> C1*C2 + C1*V. We can't do this if   │
│ C1*(C2+V) is NSW                                             │
│ +      // and C1*C2 or C1*V overflows.                       │
│ +      if (Add->getNumOperands() == 2 &&                     │
│ containsConstantInAddMulChain(Add) &&                        │
│ +          !hasFlags(OrigFlags, SCEV::FlagNSW)) {            │
│          const SCEV *LHS = getMulExpr(LHSC,                  │
│ Add->getOperand(0),                                          │
│                                       SCEV::FlagAnyWrap,     │
│ Depth + 1);                                                  │
│          const SCEV *RHS = getMulExpr(LHSC,                  │
│ Add->getOperand(1),                                          │
│                                       SCEV::FlagAnyWrap,     │
│ Depth + 1);                                                  │
│          return getAddExpr(LHS, RHS, SCEV::FlagAnyWrap,      │
│ Depth + 1);                                                  │
│        }                                                     │
│ -                                                            │
│        if (Ops[0]->isAllOnesValue()) {                       │
│          // If we have a mul by -1 of an add, try            │
│ distributing the -1 among the                                │
│          // add operands.                                    │
│                                                              │
│ ```                                                          │
